Mystery solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from being able to tickle themselves. This was found out by scientists at Humboldt University in Berlin with the help of experiments in rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. Progress has also been made on the question of why children defend themselves so violently against tickling, only to demand more.
Finally, it was also shown why the approach of a tickling hand alone triggers laughter even before the touch. This is due to a low-lying layer in the cerebrum, which triggers the laughter even when tickling is expected.
According to the data, previous research showed that rats react with "laughter" in the ultrasound area when they are tickled by humans. This "laughter" is conveyed by the part of the cerebral cortex that serves the central processing of the haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touch
So far, it has been assumed that the brain can distinguish between self-touch and touch by others - that is why people cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers now found out during the experiments on the rats that the laughter as well as the activity of the area of the cerebral cortex in question are suppressed during self-touch. This is also the case when living things clean themselves. During the external touch and the tickling by the scientists, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh about were increased.
But if the self-touch and touch by others happen at the same time, the laughter is also suppressed. This suggests that the brain of the rat cannot distinguish between self-touch and contact by others. The new findings suggested that people can't tickle themselves because self-touching activates a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. In the process, they sometimes broke off this initiation prematurely in the experiment, showed flight behavior or frightening rigidity. This ambivalence is similar to the behavior of children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioral reaction that is the same in rats and people.
