Study on causes of heart disease
Smoking, overweight, unhealthy diet - there are risk factors for cardiovascular disease. But what really triggers heart failure or an infarction? Hamburg researchers now want to take a close look at the genetic material of 9000 healthy and sick people.
Through the analysis of the genetic material of 9000 people, Hamburg and Swiss scientists want to find out the causes of cardiovascular diseases in more detail.
The research project is the largest of its kind in the German-speaking world, the University Hospital Hamburg-Eppendorf (UKE) announced on Friday. The Kühne Foundation is funding the project with €12.5 million. The Davos High Mountain Hospital, which is owned by the Foundation, and the University Hospital Zurich are involved from Switzerland.
Overweight, smoking and unhealthy diets are among the main influencing risk factors for cardiovascular disease. Genetic factors determine the risk. However, the interaction between genes and external influences is insufficiently known, it said. Now, the scientists want to compare the complete genetic material of 8000 healthy people with that of 1000 former patients of the University Heart and Vascular Center at the UKE.
Currently, in more than 4000 of the approximately 20,000 relevant human genes, possible disease-causing changes of the DNA - so-called mutations - are known, it said the hospital. Every year, about 200 are added.
According to the initiators, the aim of the five-year project is to develop new options for the prevention, detection and treatment of cardiac arrhythmias, heart failure and heart attacks. The data could also benefit in the study of other common diseases, according to Stefan Blankenberg, head of the University Heart and Vascular Center. New insights into the interaction between the heart and the brain, the heart and kidneys as well as cancers are possible.
The chairman of the Kühne Foundation, Klaus-Michael Kühne (82), also emphasized that there is a firm will to use the data to investigate other diseases. The clinic of the foundation in Davos has so far mainly treated allergies. Now a Center for Cardiovascular Precision Medicine will be created on the medical campus there and a professorship for bioinformatics will be created. To justify his commitment, the logistics entrepreneur, who lives in Switzerland, said that he had been operated on the open heart in Hamburg three years ago and was very grateful.
The biosamples of the healthy participants come from hamburgers, who also participate in the "Hamburg City Health Study". With 45,000 subjects, this is the largest local health study in the world, according to the hospital. When decoding genetic materials, strict attention is paid to the protection of the anonymized data, the scientists assured. It is about a petabyte (1000 terabytes) of data, said Holger Moch of the University Hospital Zurich.
The genetic material of a human being can be decrypted within 24 hours today, according to the UKE. The pure material costs for this would be 1300 euros. The first gene sequencing worldwide, the results of which were published in 2001, cost several hundred million euros. The study is scheduled to take place on 1. Start in October, and all 9000 samples are to be analyzed by the end of 2020. The following year, initial results are expected.
