In addition to pests, diseases, alien species, unsustainable logging and the growth of cities are also causes for the threat, the World Conservation Union (IUCN) reported in Brussels on Friday. It has examined the stocks of all 454 tree species known in Europe. Of these, 265 are not found on any other continent. Of these 265, 58 percent are threatened. 66 would already be at the highest level of danger and thus before the extinction.
The IUCN divides endangered species into six categories: from "potentially endangered" to "at risk," "highly endangered," "at risk of extinction" and "extinct in nature." In total, it lists more than 28,000 animal and plant species worldwide as endangered.
Ebere ash and wild horse chestnut threatened
