Aegean: Baby and four other children drown in boat crash
While capsizing a refugee boat in the Aegean Sea, a baby and four other children drowned. A total of seven people died in the accident, as the Greek coast guard announced on Friday. The nationalities are still unclear.
The boat sank near the Greek island of Inousses, which lies between the island of Chios and the Turkish mainland. Four children, three women and five men were rescued.
Hundreds of migrants from Turkey are currently moving to the Greek islands in the east of the Aegean Sea. Last year, 174 people were killed on this route, according to the United Nations Refugee Agency (UNHCR). German Interior Minister Horst Seehofer has now announced that he intends to visit both countries.
Together with his French colleague and the responsible EU commissioner, he wants to "inform himself in Turkey about the refugee situation," Seehofer said on Friday. Afterwards, he wanted to learn more about the "administrative problems of the Greeks" in Athens, in order to be able to help with the management.
A spokeswoman for the EU Commission confirmed on Friday Seehofer's planned trip with EU Home Affairs Commissioner Dimitris Avramopoulos and France's Interior Minister Christophe Castaner.
In Greece, an unusual number of migrants continue to arrive from Turkey. On Tuesday alone, 654 people transferred to the Greek islands, the Greek Ministry of Civil Protection said on Wednesday.
Does the Turkey deal still work?
The increased figures have recently raised doubts about the functioning of the EU-Turkey agreement concluded in 2016. This stipulates that the EU can send back all refugees and migrants who come to the Greek islands illegally via Turkey. In return, the EU wanted to take in a Syrian refugee from Turkey for every deported Syrian.
However, the processing of asylum applications is progressing only painstakingly on the Greek side because of the lack of staff. Lesbos, Chios, Samos, Leros and Kos are waiting for just under 29 400 people, according to the Citizens' Protection Ministry. The worst situation is on Lesvos: 5200 migrants are currently housed in a warehouse with capacity for 650 people.
Never since the entry into force of the EU-Turkey refugee pact in March 2016 have there been so many, reported the state broadcaster.
