Greens politician must answer for embarrassing photo breakdown
The head of the Canadian Greens, Elizabeth May, in the election campaign - was the cup manipulated for this reason?
The Canadian Green Party leader holds a reusable cup in her hand in a photo. But now it came out: The cup was manipulated.
Ottawa/Canada - It has gone unnoticed for quite a long time - and finally noticed. Elizabeth May, the head of the Canadian Greens, has never held the reusable coffee cup with metal straw in her hand. On the party's website, she was seen in a photo with this cup, in conversation with citizens. However, the photo had already been published and also disseminated to the media - and there the cup was still a sneerous (cardboard) cup, as the Canadian National Post reported.
Greens leader must answer for photo breakdown
The National Post then accused May of manipulation and that the party was producing fake news to appear more credible on the issue of "environmental protection". And this in the middle of an election campaign for the lower house election, in which Trudeau is also having an increasingly difficult time because of a bribery scandal.
The photo went viral on social media, fueling discussion about fake news. One user shares a juxtaposition of the photos and writes: "The Greens manipulate a photo of their chairmen to hide their disposable cup".
May was shocked and said on her blog that she did not know about this action. To underline this, she immediately posted the original: she, in conversation with citizens, a cup in her hand. But the one, she put it right, was made of bamboo. She always brought him. A spokeswoman for the party said it was just a matter of housing the party logo in the picture, not covering up anything. Only a snippet of the photo can be seen on the website.
May writes that she is sorry for the employee who did this. "I don't want to call him stupid, but there was nothing to hide," she tells the Guardian, and at the same time asked for something from her over-committed team: "If they feel like editing a picture again, they couldn't do something with my face, so I look younger?"
The German Greens have also fallen into shitstorms because of their use of single-use plastic or because of air travel - but their pictures were not photoshopped. So the boss of the Bavarian Greens, Katharina Schulze, ate on holiday ice cream with plastic spoons, as merkur.de* reported.
Influencer wants free upgrade: Lifelong flight ban at Cathay
Jaqueline Ng was promised an upgrade by Cathay Pacific. But when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed to board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Get an upgrade for the business class spontaneously - that's what many passengers dream of. Sometimes they are lucky, and the staff at check-in offer a change from economy class for free.
However, this case shows how not to do it: A self-declared influencer has actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. Jaqueline Ng is followed by more than 65,000 users on Instagram. On the 30. May she is from Taiwan to New York and on 7. June flown back.
On the outbound flight, staff refused to upgrade Jaqueline, although she had presented an email in which Cathay Pacific allegedly offered her an upgrade. The influencer wants to have received the letter from a marketing employee of the airline. The airline, on the other hand, accuses Jaqueline of forging the mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman is said to have presented the same mail, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK airport were skeptical: they followed up at the headquarters. And in fact, the employee from whom the mail is allegedly originated is said to have denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. That also confirmed the mail system, where the messages did not show up.
Airline staff at the airport canceled Jaqueline's ticket and imposed a lifetime flight ban with Cathay Pacific. For $1,400 (around 1,280 euros) she had to buy a new flight ticket to Taiwan.
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests. Although Cathay had reimbursed her the price for her original ticket, Jaqueline also demanded the cost of the new ticket back.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: For Cathay, the influencer has committed fraud, she remains locked for future flights. The airline’s terms and conditions also state that it does not have to pay for the new flight. Jaqueline doesn't want to settle for that - and is now turning on a lawyer.
Oil prices give way after report on Yemen ceasefire
Oil prices fell by more than a dollar in noon on Friday afternoon. Most recently, a barrel (159 litres) of the North Sea variety Brent cost $61.83 - around 1.4 percent less than the previous day. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell 1.3 percent to $55.77.
The trigger for the price slide was a Wall Street Journal report on a Yemen ceasefire. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone attack on the oil facilities in Saudi Arabia had brought five percent of the world's oil production to a standstill in mid-September. The Houthi rebels allied with Iran in the civil war-torn country of Yemen had reclaimed the attacks for themselves. Saudi Arabia, like the U.S. government, blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse political tension in the region.
If an agreement is actually reached, one could focus on growth and demand worries, Ole Hansen, head of the commodity strategy department at Saxo Bank told Bloomberg news agency.
Oil prices are thus continuing its downward movement of the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had still cost up to nearly $59, while Brent had nearly $65.
Most recently, Bloomberg had reported, citing insiders, that repair work on oil facilities in Saudi Arabia is progressing faster than thought after the attack in mid-September. Accordingly, the production volume has again reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original quantity.
Recently, there have been several press releases, citing insiders who report rapid progress by the state-owned oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. But commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, some relaxation was indicated in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: The British oil tanker "Stena Impero" is more than two months after the arrest by Iran and the recently granted release on the way to leave the port. The crew is now preparing the departure, while the ship is still anchored, shipping company chief Erik Hånell told the Swedish radio in a text message on Friday morning.
However, the U.S. announced that it would move missiles and soldiers to Saudi Arabia to the Iranian arch-enemy. Fears of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the US and the UK have at times pushed up oil prices significantly in recent weeks.
