North Korea considers third summit of Trump and Kim questionable
North Korea has raised doubts that a third summit of leader Kim Jong-un and US President Donald Trump will soon come in the nuclear dispute. The meaning and prospects of success of such a meeting are questionable because of a lack of progress in implementing agreements of the first summit in Singapore, top diplomat Kim Kye-gwan said on Friday, according to the agency KCNA.
The U.S. has so far done nothing to implement the summit's decisions the previous year, North Korea's adviser to the North Korean Foreign Ministry said. He also criticized tightening U.S. sanctions and the joint military maneuvers of the US and South Korea. But he hopes for a "wise" and "courageous" decision of Trump, so that it comes again to a rapprochement.
Trump had said on Monday that he wanted to know what a third summit should bring with Kim before he agreed to do so. Negotiations on disarmament of North Korea's nuclear and missile program have stalled since the failed second summit of Trump and Kim in Hanoi in February. In June, both met in the Demilitarized Zone between the two Korean states. In doing so, they agreed to revive the consultations, but so far without much success.
